 application, right-click on the Lookup  Data Structure  for which you want to create a Filter Set and select  New  /  Filter Set : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/1b2b2ada28fb56e4fe691eee5b2d51dac112e9be.png]\nDescription: The image features a software interface with a \u0022Model Browser\u0022 panel, showing a structured view of a project named \u0022myapplication.\u0022 Within the hierarchy, the \u0022Common\u0022 and \u0022Data\u0022 sections are expanded, revealing a \u0022Constants\u0022 section which includes \u0022Data Structures\u0022 with sub-items such as \u0022spreadsheet,\u0022 \u0022_system,\u0022 \u0022Dimensions,\u0022 and \u0022myapplication.\u0022 A drop-down menu is visible, indicating options associated with the \u0022Filter Set\u0022 entity, including actions like \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022New Group,\u0022 \u0022Repeat New (F12),\u0022 \u0022Actions,\u0022 \u0022Convert To,\u0022 \u0022Move To Package,\u0022 \u0022Expand All,\u0022 and \u0022Edit item.\u0022 The interface appears to be used for organizing data structures and entities within a data modeling environment.\n\n\n  \n \n   Remember to create the Filter Set for the Data Structure used in the Lookup you want to use in your drop-down menu. Such Data Structure names follow our naming convention and start with  Lookup , e.g.,  LookupTask_Name_GetId . \n \n   Name your Filter Set \n In the Filter Set properties, name your set using the naming convention  GetBy  \u002B parameter, e.g.: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/78108dfb2d40ff3de4857e59d20d5af094154ad7.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface panel titled \u0022GetByDueDate,\u0022 which is part of a filter set configuration. The panel includes sections labeled \u0022(Info)\u0022 and \u0022Misc.\u0022 Under \u0022(Info),\u0022 there are three rows showing attributes: \u0022Ancestors\u0022 set to False, \u0022Inheritable\u0022 also set to False, and \u0022Name\u0022 indicated as \u0022GetByDueDate.\u0022 Under \u0022Misc,\u0022 the attribute \u0022IsDynamic\u0022 is set to False. The purpose of this interface is to define and manage properties related to a specific filter set in a software application, likely for querying data based on due dates.\n\n\n  \n Save it. \n   Add Filter(s) \n Right-click on your Filter Set and select  New  /  Filter : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/7d0161385b1098033f01de26446061dd7fb4fc08.png]\nDescription: The image displays a Model Browser interface within a software application, specifically titled \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The hierarchy includes sections labeled \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 \u0022Constants,\u0022 and \u0022Data Structures.\u0022 Under \u0022Data Structures,\u0022 there are several nested items: \u0022myapplication,\u0022 \u0022__spreadsheet,\u0022 \u0022__system,\u0022 \u0022Dimensions,\u0022 and \u0022Entities.\u0022 The \u0022myapplication\u0022 section contains fields such as \u0022LookupPriority_Name_GetId,\u0022 \u0022LookupStatus_Name_GetId,\u0022 \u0022Priority,\u0022 \u0022Status,\u0022 and \u0022Task.\u0022 The interface features a menu with options for \u0022Filter,\u0022 \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022New Group,\u0022 and \u0022Repeat New\u0022 (F12), alongside a context menu item \u0022GetByDueDate.\u0022 The apparent purpose of the UI is to manage and organize various data structures relevant to the application.\n\n\n  \n   Configure Filter(s) \n In the Filter Set Filter details, select your  Entity  and  Filter , and the  Name  will be created automatically. For example: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/d/d9ba70b166b1fbe69462add8865955eecc64ba2f.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for managing a data schema item titled \u0022Task_TasksAfterDeadline.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__"